<section xml:id="section-vector-geom-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title><term>norm (of a vector <m>\uvec{v}</m>)</term></title>
	<idx><h>norm</h><h>in <m>\R^n</m></h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>norm (in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<p>the quantity <m>\unorm{v} = \sqrt{v_1^2+v_2^2+\dotsb+v_n^2}</m>; also called the
	<term>length</term>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>length</h></idx>
	or
	<term>magnitude</term>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>magnitude</h></idx>
	of <m>\uvec{v}</m></p>
	</li>

	<li><title><term>unit vector</term></title>
	<idx><h>unit vector</h><h>in <m>\R^n</m></h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>unit (in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<p>a vector whose norm is equal to <m>1</m></p>
	</li>

	<li><title><term>normalization (of a vector <m>\uvec{v}</m>)</term></title>
	<idx><h>normalization</h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>normalization</h></idx>
	<p>the unit vector <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{\unorm{v}}\,\uvec{v}</m></p>
	</li>

	<li><title><term>distance (between two vectors <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m>)</term></title>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>distance</h></idx>
	<p> the distance between the terminal points of the two vectors when their initial points are placed at the same point; can be computed as <m>\norm{\uvec{u}-\uvec{v}}</m> (or equivalently as <m>\norm{\uvec{v}-\uvec{u}}</m>) </p>
	</li>

	<li><title><term>dot product (of two vectors <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m> of the same dimension)</term></title>
	<idx><h>dot product</h><h>real</h></idx>
	<p> the quantity <me>\udotprod{u}{v} = u_1 v_1 + u_2 v_2 + \dotsb + u_n v_n; </me> also referred to as the
	<term>Euclidean inner product</term>
	<idx><h>Euclidean</h><h>inner product</h></idx>
	<idx><h>inner product</h><h>Euclidean</h></idx>
	or
	<term>standard inner product</term>
	<idx><h>standard</h><h>inner product (on <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>inner product</h><h>standard</h></idx>
	of <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li><title><term>angle (between two vectors <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m> of the same dimension)</term></title>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>angle (in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<p>
	the angle <m>\theta</m> satisfying both
	<md><mrow>
		0\amp\le\theta\le\pi \amp \amp\text{and} \amp \cos \theta \amp= \frac{\udotprod{u}{v}}{\unorm{u}\unorm{v}}
	</mrow></md>
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
